Access specifiers control member visibility in inheritance:

```java
package package1;
public class Parent {
    private int privateVar = 1;      // Not inherited
    int defaultVar = 2;               // Inherited within package
    protected int protectedVar = 3;   // Inherited everywhere
    public int publicVar = 4;         // Inherited everywhere

    private void privateMethod() { }
    void defaultMethod() { }
    protected void protectedMethod() { }
    public void publicMethod() { }
}

package package1;
class SamePackageChild extends Parent {
    void access() {
        // privateVar not accessible
        defaultVar = 10;      // Accessible (same package)
        protectedVar = 20;    // Accessible
        publicVar = 30;       // Accessible

        defaultMethod();      // Accessible
        protectedMethod();    // Accessible
        publicMethod();       // Accessible
    }
}

package package2;
import package1.Parent;
class DifferentPackageChild extends Parent {
    void access() {
        // privateVar, defaultVar not accessible
        protectedVar = 20;    // Accessible (via inheritance)
        publicVar = 30;       // Accessible

        protectedMethod();    // Accessible
        publicMethod();       // Accessible
    }
}
```

The 'super' keyword has three main uses:

```java
class Animal {
    String sound = "Animal sound";

    Animal() {
        System.out.println("Animal constructor");
    }

    Animal(String type) {
        System.out.println("Animal: " + type);
    }

    void makeSound() {
        System.out.println("Animal making sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    String sound = "Bark";

    // 1. super() to call parent constructor
    Dog() {
        super();  // Calls Animal()
        System.out.println("Dog constructor");
    }

    Dog(String breed) {
        super("Mammal");  // Calls Animal(String)
        System.out.println("Dog breed: " + breed);
    }

    void display() {
        // 2. super to access parent variable
        System.out.println("Child sound: " + sound);
        System.out.println("Parent sound: " + super.sound);
    }

    @Override
    void makeSound() {
        // 3. super to call parent method
        super.makeSound();
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}

// Usage
public class SuperDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Dog dog = new Dog();
        dog.display();
        dog.makeSound();

        Dog labrador = new Dog("Labrador");
    }
}
```

Method overriding allows subclass to provide specific implementation of parent method.

**Rules:**
1. Same method name and parameters
2. Same or covariant return type
3. Cannot have weaker access modifier
4. Cannot override private, static, final methods
5. Can use @Override annotation

```java
class Bank {
    protected double getInterestRate() {
        return 4.0;
    }

    void display() {
        System.out.println("Bank class");
    }
}

class SBI extends Bank {
    @Override
    public double getInterestRate() {  // Weaker? No, protected to public is stronger
        return 6.5;
    }

    @Override
    void display() {
        super.display();
        System.out.println("SBI Bank");
    }
}

class HDFC extends Bank {
    @Override
    public double getInterestRate() {
        return 7.0;
    }
}

public class OverridingDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Bank bank = new Bank();
        System.out.println("Bank rate: " + bank.getInterestRate());

        SBI sbi = new SBI();
        System.out.println("SBI rate: " + sbi.getInterestRate());
        sbi.display();

        // Runtime polymorphism
        Bank ref = new HDFC();
        System.out.println("HDFC rate: " + ref.getInterestRate());
    }
}
```

Constructor chaining is the process where constructors call their parent constructors using super().

```java
class GrandParent {
    GrandParent() {
        System.out.println("GrandParent constructor");
    }

    GrandParent(String name) {
        System.out.println("GrandParent: " + name);
    }
}

class Parent extends GrandParent {
    Parent() {
        super();  // Implicit if not written
        System.out.println("Parent constructor");
    }

    Parent(String name) {
        super(name);  // Must explicitly call parameterized constructor
        System.out.println("Parent: " + name);
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    Child() {
        super();  // Calls Parent()
        System.out.println("Child constructor");
    }

    Child(String name) {
        super(name);  // Must call Parent(String)
        System.out.println("Child: " + name);
    }
}

// What if parent lacks default constructor?
class Vehicle {
    String type;
    Vehicle(String type) {  // No default constructor
        this.type = type;
    }
}

class Car extends Vehicle {
    Car() {
        super("Four-wheeler");  // MUST explicitly call super
    }

    Car(String brand) {
        super("Four-wheeler");  // MUST explicitly call super first
        System.out.println("Brand: " + brand);
    }
}
```

**Key Points:**
- First statement in constructor must be super() or this()
- If parent lacks no-arg constructor, child must explicitly call super with parameters
- Constructor chaining ensures all parent classes are initialized before child

Abstract classes are blueprints that cannot be instantiated.

**Properties of Abstract Class:**
1. Cannot be instantiated
2. Can have constructors (called via super())
3. Can have abstract and concrete methods
4. Can have instance variables and static members
5. Can extend only one class (abstract or concrete)
6. Can implement multiple interfaces
7. Can have final methods (cannot be overridden)
8. Can have static methods

```java
abstract class Shape {
    // Instance variables
    protected String color;
    protected static int shapeCount = 0;

    // Constructor
    Shape(String color) {
        this.color = color;
        shapeCount++;
        System.out.println("Shape created: " + color);
    }

    // Abstract methods (no body)
    abstract double area();
    abstract double perimeter();

    // Concrete method
    public void display() {
        System.out.println("This is a " + color + " shape");
        System.out.println("Area: " + area());
        System.out.println("Perimeter: " + perimeter());
    }

    // Static method
    public static int getShapeCount() {
        return shapeCount;
    }

    // Final method (cannot be overridden)
    public final void description() {
        System.out.println("Shape is an abstract representation");
    }
}

class Circle extends Shape {
    private double radius;

    Circle(String color, double radius) {
        super(color);
        this.radius = radius;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return Math.PI * radius * radius;
    }

    @Override
    double perimeter() {
        return 2 * Math.PI * radius;
    }
}

class Rectangle extends Shape {
    private double length, width;

    Rectangle(String color, double length, double width) {
        super(color);
        this.length = length;
        this.width = width;
    }

    @Override
    double area() {
        return length * width;
    }

    @Override
    double perimeter() {
        return 2 * (length + width);
    }
}

// Usage
public class AbstractDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Shape s = new Shape("Red"); // ERROR: Cannot instantiate

        Shape circle = new Circle("Red", 5);
        Shape rectangle = new Rectangle("Blue", 4, 6);

        circle.display();
        rectangle.display();

        System.out.println("Total shapes: " + Shape.getShapeCount());
    }
}
```

Runtime polymorphism allows parent reference to hold child object, and overridden method of child is called at runtime.

```java
abstract class Payment {
    abstract void processPayment(double amount);

    void receipt() {
        System.out.println("Payment receipt generated");
    }
}

class CreditCardPayment extends Payment {
    @Override
    void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing ₹" + amount + " via Credit Card");
        System.out.println("2% transaction fee applied");
    }
}

class PayPalPayment extends Payment {
    @Override
    void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing ₹" + amount + " via PayPal");
        System.out.println("1.5% transaction fee applied");
    }
}

class CashPayment extends Payment {
    @Override
    void processPayment(double amount) {
        System.out.println("Processing ₹" + amount + " via Cash");
        System.out.println("No transaction fee");
    }
}

public class RuntimePolymorphismDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Parent reference, child objects
        Payment payment;

        payment = new CreditCardPayment();
        payment.processPayment(1000);  // CreditCard version called

        payment = new PayPalPayment();
        payment.processPayment(2000);  // PayPal version called

        payment = new CashPayment();
        payment.processPayment(500);   // Cash version called

        // Polymorphic array
        Payment[] payments = {
            new CreditCardPayment(),
            new PayPalPayment(),
            new CashPayment()
        };

        for(Payment p : payments) {
            p.processPayment(100);
            p.receipt();
            System.out.println("---");
        }
    }
}
```

**Key Points:**
- Method resolution happens at runtime based on actual object
- Enables loose coupling and extensibility
- Parent class methods can be overridden
- Cannot override static, private, final methods

**Types of Inheritance in Java:**

1. **Single Inheritance:** One child extends one parent
```java
class Parent { }
class Child extends Parent { }
```

2. **Multilevel Inheritance:** Chain of inheritance
```java
class GrandParent { }
class Parent extends GrandParent { }
class Child extends Parent { }
```

3. **Hierarchical Inheritance:** Multiple children extend one parent
```java
class Parent { }
class Child1 extends Parent { }
class Child2 extends Parent { }
```

4. **Multiple Inheritance (Not supported via classes):** One child extending multiple parents
```java
// NOT allowed in Java
class Child extends Parent1, Parent2 { }  // Compilation Error
```

5. **Hybrid Inheritance (Not supported):** Combination of multiple and hierarchical

**Why Java doesn't support multiple inheritance?**

**Diamond Problem:** If two parent classes have the same method, Java can't decide which to inherit.

```java
class A {
    void display() { System.out.println("A"); }
}
class B {
    void display() { System.out.println("B"); }
}
// class C extends A, B { }  // Which display() to inherit? Ambiguity!
```

**How to achieve multiple inheritance using interfaces:**

```java
interface Flyable {
    void fly();
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Can fly");
    }
}

interface Swimmable {
    void swim();
    default void show() {
        System.out.println("Can swim");
    }
}

class Duck implements Flyable, Swimmable {
    @Override
    public void fly() {
        System.out.println("Duck flying");
    }

    @Override
    public void swim() {
        System.out.println("Duck swimming");
    }

    // Resolve default method conflict
    @Override
    public void show() {
        Flyable.super.show();
        Swimmable.super.show();
        System.out.println("Duck can both fly and swim");
    }
}

// Multiple interface inheritance
interface Animal { }
interface Bird extends Animal { }
interface Mammal extends Animal { }
interface Bat extends Bird, Mammal { }  // Valid - interfaces support multiple inheritance

public class InheritanceTypesDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Duck duck = new Duck();
        duck.fly();
        duck.swim();
        duck.show();
    }
}
```

**Static in Inheritance:**

```java
class Parent {
    static int staticVar = 10;
    int instanceVar = 20;

    static {
        System.out.println("Parent static block");
    }

    static void staticMethod() {
        System.out.println("Parent static method: " + staticVar);
    }

    void instanceMethod() {
        System.out.println("Parent instance method");
    }
}

class Child extends Parent {
    static int staticVar = 100;  // Hides Parent.staticVar

    static {
        System.out.println("Child static block");
    }

    static void staticMethod() {  // Method hiding, not overriding
        System.out.println("Child static method: " + staticVar);
    }

    void instanceMethod() {
        System.out.println("Child instance method");
    }
}

public class StaticInheritanceDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Static members belong to class, not objects
        System.out.println("Parent.staticVar: " + Parent.staticVar);
        System.out.println("Child.staticVar: " + Child.staticVar);

        Parent.staticMethod();
        Child.staticMethod();

        // Access via objects (not recommended)
        Parent p = new Parent();
        Child c = new Child();
        Parent ref = new Child();

        System.out.println("\nAccess via parent reference to child:");
        System.out.println("staticVar: " + ref.staticVar);  // 10 (Parent's)
        ref.staticMethod();  // Parent's static method
        ref.instanceMethod(); // Child's instance method (overridden)

        // Static blocks execute when class loads
        // Output:
        // Parent static block
        // Child static block
    }
}
```

**Static in Abstract Classes:**

```java
abstract class Database {
    static String connectionUrl;
    static int activeConnections = 0;

    static {
        connectionUrl = "jdbc:mysql://localhost:3306/mydb";
        System.out.println("Database static block executed");
    }

    static void setConnectionUrl(String url) {
        connectionUrl = url;
    }

    static int getActiveConnections() {
        return activeConnections;
    }

    abstract void connect();

    static void displayConfig() {
        System.out.println("Connection URL: " + connectionUrl);
        System.out.println("Active Connections: " + activeConnections);
    }
}

class MySQLDatabase extends Database {
    @Override
    void connect() {
        activeConnections++;
        System.out.println("Connected to MySQL at " + connectionUrl);
    }
}

class PostgreSQLDatabase extends Database {
    @Override
    void connect() {
        activeConnections++;
        System.out.println("Connected to PostgreSQL at " + connectionUrl);
    }
}

public class StaticAbstractDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // Call static methods on abstract class
        Database.displayConfig();
        Database.setConnectionUrl("jdbc:postgresql://localhost:5432/mydb");

        MySQLDatabase mysql = new MySQLDatabase();
        PostgreSQLDatabase psql = new PostgreSQLDatabase();

        mysql.connect();
        psql.connect();

        System.out.println("Total connections: " + Database.getActiveConnections());

        // Static methods cannot be overridden
        Database.displayConfig();  // Still shows parent's static method
    }
}
```

**Key Points:**
- Static members belong to class level, inherited but not overridden
- Static methods are hidden, not overridden (no polymorphism)
- Static blocks execute when class is first loaded
- Abstract classes can have static members
- Static methods can be called without instance

**No, abstract classes cannot be instantiated directly.** However, there are alternative ways to use them:

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    String brand;

    Vehicle(String brand) {
        this.brand = brand;
    }

    abstract void start();
    abstract void stop();

    void displayBrand() {
        System.out.println("Brand: " + brand);
    }
}

// 1. Using concrete subclass (Most common)
class Car extends Vehicle {
    Car(String brand) {
        super(brand);
    }

    @Override
    void start() {
        System.out.println(brand + " car started");
    }

    @Override
    void stop() {
        System.out.println(brand + " car stopped");
    }
}

// 2. Using anonymous inner class
abstract class Greeting {
    abstract void sayHello();
}

// 3. Using lambda (for functional interfaces with single abstract method)
@FunctionalInterface
interface Calculator {
    int calculate(int a, int b);
}

public class AbstractInstantiationDemo {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        // DIRECT INSTANTIATION - NOT POSSIBLE
        // Vehicle v = new Vehicle("Toyota");  // COMPILATION ERROR

        // Method 1: Through concrete subclass
        Vehicle car = new Car("Toyota");
        car.start();
        car.stop();
        car.displayBrand();

        // Method 2: Anonymous inner class
        Greeting greeting = new Greeting() {
            @Override
            void sayHello() {
                System.out.println("Hello from anonymous class!");
            }
        };
        greeting.sayHello();

        // Method 3: Using lambda expression (functional interface)
        Calculator add = (a, b) -> a + b;
        Calculator multiply = (a, b) -> a * b;

        System.out.println("Addition: " + add.calculate(10, 20));
        System.out.println("Multiplication: " + multiply.calculate(10, 20));

        // Method 4: Using builder pattern with abstract class
        AbstractBuilder builder = new ConcreteBuilder();
        Product product = builder.build();
        product.show();
    }
}

// Method 4: Builder pattern example
abstract class AbstractBuilder {
    abstract Product build();
}

class ConcreteBuilder extends AbstractBuilder {
    @Override
    Product build() {
        return new Product("Built product");
    }
}

class Product {
    String name;
    Product(String name) { this.name = name; }
    void show() { System.out.println("Product: " + name); }
}
```

**Why can't we instantiate abstract classes?**
1. Abstract classes are incomplete (may have abstract methods without body)
2. Calling abstract methods would cause runtime error
3. It enforces proper design - forcing implementation before use

**Common Misconceptions:**
```java
// Abstract class with constructor
abstract class Test {
    Test() {
        System.out.println("Abstract class constructor");
    }
    abstract void show();
}

class TestImpl extends Test {
    TestImpl() {
        super();  // Constructor is called when subclass is instantiated
    }

    @Override
    void show() {
        System.out.println("Implementation");
    }
}

// The abstract class constructor runs, but we never instantiated Test directly
Test obj = new TestImpl();  // Valid - Test constructor executes
// This doesn't mean Test was instantiated, only its constructor was called
```

**Best Practices:**
- Use concrete subclass for reusable implementations
- Use anonymous inner class for one-time use
- Use lambda expressions for functional interfaces
- Abstract classes provide partial implementation - always extend them

